                        </article>                </li>
        </ul>
</aside><p class="bb-p">“It’s only a small cost to pay for men and women get a massive advantage,” says Bovens. But few companies are considering this point, he argues. “What we are seeing from design proposals is [companies] retrofit the entire thing, and basically don’t make any changes. Or they keep the gender specific bathrooms and then add a gender neutral bathroom to it.”</p><p class="bb-p">Both of these designs are problematic because they do not address safety concerns for women, and may make people who struggle to go to the toilet in public spaces more uncomfortable.</p><p class="bb-p">That’s why designers are proposing an alternative that could address privacy, accessibility and equality issues at the same time. <a href="https://www.stalled.online/" class="bb-a">Stalled!</a>, a group of academics, came up with a design that involves rows of super loos and larger cubicles for disabled users – which could fit in the same space as segregated bathrooms.</p><p class="bb-p">“We call ourselves binary abolitionists. And we believe that the key problem is the existing configuration of sex segregated restrooms that sorts people into two problematic categories, male and female,” explains Joel Sanders, an academic at the Yale School of Architecture.</p><p class="bb-p">“We even advocate eliminating the hallway, and no longer even making a restroom sequestered space of a corridor, but making it a porous extension of the corridor, which actually gives us more space,” he says. For this to work, companies would have to ensure that toilets are on a visible corridor or open space, rather than tucked away. </p><aside class="a-sidebar-content">
        <h4 class="a-sidebar-content__title">Read next</h4>
        <ul class="a-sidebar-content__list">
                <li class="a-sidebar-content__list-item">
                        <article class="c-card c-card--portrait-small">
                        		<a href="/article/working-from-home-relationships" class="c-card__link c-card__link--article ">How to work at home on lockdown without ruining your relationship</a>

                        	<div class="c-card__obj">
                        		<div class="c-card__obj__header">
                        			<div class="c-card__images">

                        						<div class="c-card__image c-card__image--square ">
                        								        <img src="/static/img/tiny.gif" data-src="https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/5LZZAO1zRkz/crop/200/square/f/wired-couples.jpg" data-srcset="https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/5LZZAO1zRkz/crop/200/square/f/wired-couples.jpg 200w, https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/5LZZAO1zRkz/crop/300/square/f/wired-couples.jpg 300w, https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/5LZZAO1zRkz/crop/400/square/f/wired-couples.jpg 400w, https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/5LZZAO1zRkz/crop/600/square/f/wired-couples.jpg 600w" data-sizes="auto" class="c-image c-image--lazyload "  />
                        								        <noscript>
                        								            <img src="https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/5LZZAO1zRkz/crop/200/square/f/wired-couples.jpg" class=""   />
                        								        </noscript>

                        						</div>



                        			</div>
                        		</div>

                        		<div class="c-card__obj__body">
                        			<div class="c-card__header">

                        					<h3 class="c-card__title">
                        					    <span>How to work at home on lockdown without ruining your relationship</span>
                        					</h3>


                        				<hr class="c-card__separator" />
                        			</div>

                        			<div class="c-card__footer">

                        				        <p class="c-card__byline">
                        				            <span class="c-card__byline-prefix">By</span>
                        				            <span class="c-card__byline-name">Sophia Epstein</span>
                        				        </p>

                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </article>                </li>
        </ul>
</aside><p class="bb-p">Of course, this design won’t solve all issues – it doesn’t necessarily take into account religious restrictions, or people who want to be segregated by sex. But it could help people with disabilities or carers, who are rarely considered in this debate.</p><p class="bb-p">Edward Warner, chief executive of accessible design specialist Motionspot, says that if super loos could all be made large enough to work for disabled people and allow them to avoid self-segregating, it would be “utopia”. </p><p class="bb-p">“Businesses need to educate staff on when to use disabled toilets,” he says. “But I always think that if you improve the design, people are more likely to take care of it.” </p><p class="bb-p">He points out that it is not only those with physical disabilities that need access to specialist restrooms – companies like Barclays are trying to design provisions for employees with sensory development issues, such as autism. Until people are told to stop hogging the loos, the only other alternative is for disabled people to try to manage in the poorly-designed spaces available to all.</p><p class="bb-p">“A lot of disabled toilets are locked for a reason. Apparently, they are places where people go to take drugs and have sex,” Baroness Tanni Grey-Thompson said at the House of Lords debate on gender neutral bathrooms on Wednesday. “If there’s somebody in an accessible toilet who needs to be there for a long period of time, the only other option I have is to use the women’s toilet. In that case, I have to go with the door open.”</p><aside class="a-sidebar-content">
        <h4 class="a-sidebar-content__title">Read next</h4>
        <ul class="a-sidebar-content__list">
                <li class="a-sidebar-content__list-item">
                        <article class="c-card c-card--portrait-small">
                        		<a href="/article/working-from-home-posture-back-pain" class="c-card__link c-card__link--article ">Working from home is ruining your posture. Here’s how to fix it</a>

                        	<div class="c-card__obj">
                        		<div class="c-card__obj__header">
                        			<div class="c-card__images">

                        						<div class="c-card__image c-card__image--square ">
                        								        <img src="/static/img/tiny.gif" data-src="https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/w8WvOo1k24d/crop/200/square/f/posture.jpg" data-srcset="https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/w8WvOo1k24d/crop/200/square/f/posture.jpg 200w, https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/w8WvOo1k24d/crop/300/square/f/posture.jpg 300w, https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/w8WvOo1k24d/crop/400/square/f/posture.jpg 400w, https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/w8WvOo1k24d/crop/600/square/f/posture.jpg 600w" data-sizes="auto" class="c-image c-image--lazyload "  />
                        								        <noscript>
                        								            <img src="https://wi-images.condecdn.net/image/w8WvOo1k24d/crop/200/square/f/posture.jpg" class=""   />
                        								        </noscript>

                        						</div>



                        			</div>
                        		</div>

                        		<div class="c-card__obj__body">
                        			<div class="c-card__header">

                        					<h3 class="c-card__title">
                        					    <span>Working from home is ruining your posture. Here’s how to fix it</span>
                        					</h3>


                        				<hr class="c-card__separator" />
                        			</div>

                        			<div class="c-card__footer">

                        				        <p class="c-card__byline">
                        				            <span class="c-card__byline-prefix">By</span>
                        				            <span class="c-card__byline-name">Natasha Bernal</span>
                        				        </p>

                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </article>                </li>
        </ul>
</aside><p class="bb-p">Yet it was an intervention by Lord Lucas at the House of Lords that attracted attention from trans activists, after he argued that single-sex facilities were safer for women and described the unisex lavatories in the Department for Education’s Westminster offices as “deeply unpleasant”.</p><p class="bb-p">This design, where toilets are less hidden away and therefore less likely to be misused, can help convince people to change their minds, Sanders says. “This is not only for the transgender issue, which is important, but to facilitate all kinds of people with different needs – and everybody's trying to figure this out on their own.”</p><p class="bb-p"><em class="bb-em">Natasha Bernal is WIRED's business editor. She tweets from <a href="https://twitter.com/TashaBernal" class="bb-a">@TashaBernal</a></em></p><h4 class="bb-h4" id="more-great-stories-from-wired">More great stories from WIRED</h4><p class="bb-p"><strong class="bb-strong">🏙️ A <a href="https://www.wired.co.uk/article/airbnb-scam-london" class="bb-a">huge Airbnb scam</a> is taking over London</strong></p><p class="bb-p"><strong class="bb-strong">🚙 Thinking of buying an electric car? <a href="https://www.wired.co.uk/article/electric-cars-uk-buying-guide" class="bb-a">Read this first</a></strong></p><p class="bb-p"><strong class="bb-strong">🍅 Why do modern <a href="https://www.wired.co.uk/article/why-do-uk-tomatoes-taste-bad" class="bb-a">tomatoes taste so bad?</a></strong> </p><aside class="ad__main is-hidden ad--article ad--article-rail stick-wrapper ">
